In mathematics, '''algebraic cobordism''' is an analogue of [[complex cobordism]] for smooth [[quasi-projective scheme]]s over a [[field (mathematics)|field]]. It was introduced by {{harvs|txt|first1=Marc|last1=Levine|author1-link=Marc Levine (mathematician) |first2=Fabien |last2= Morel |author2-link=Fabien Morel|year1= 2001|year2=2001b}}.

An oriented [[cohomology theory]] on the category of smooth quasi-projective schemes '''Sm''' over a field ''k'' consists of a [[contravariant functor]] ''A''* from '''Sm''' to commutative [[graded ring]]s, together with [[Pushforward (homology)|push-forward map]]s ''f''<sub>*</sub> whenever ''f'':''Y''→''X'' has relative dimension ''d'' for some ''d''. These maps have to satisfy various conditions similar to those satisfied by complex cobordism. In particular they  are "oriented", which means roughly that they behave well on [[vector bundle]]s; this is closely related to the condition that a [[generalized cohomology theory]] has a [[complex orientation]].

Over a field of characteristic 0, algebraic cobordism is the universal oriented cohomology theory  for smooth varieties. In other words there is a unique morphism of oriented cohomology theories from algebraic cobordism to any other oriented cohomology theory.

{{harvtxt|Levine|2002}} and {{harvtxt|Levine|Morel|2007}} give surveys of algebraic cobordism.

The algebraic cobordism ring of [[generalized flag variety|generalized flag varieties]] has been computed by {{harvtxt|Hornbostel|Kiritchenko|2011}}.

