In [[mathematical logic]], the '''Kanamori–McAloon theorem''', due to {{harvtxt|Kanamori|McAloon|1987}}, gives an example of an incompleteness in [[Peano arithmetic]], similar to that of the [[Paris–Harrington theorem]]. They showed that a certain finitistic special case of a theorem in [[Ramsey theory]] due to [[Paul Erdős|Erdős]] and [[Richard Rado|Rado]] is not provable in Peano arithmetic.
